201:194.name: Configuration=Filled, State=pressed, Show Icon=False
201:194.description:
Filled buttons are high-emphasis buttons.
They have the most visual impact after the FAB, and should be used for important, final actions that complete a flow, like "Save", "Join now", or "Confirm".

201:144.name: Configuration=Outlined, State=focused, Show Icon=True
201:144.description:
Outlined buttons are medium-emphasis buttons.
They contain actions that are important, but arent the primary action in an app.

Outlined buttons pair well with filled buttons to indicate an alternative, secondary action.

201:113.name: Configuration=Text, State=hovered, Show Icon=True
201:113.description:
Text buttons are low-emphasis buttons.
They are used for the lowest priority actions, especially when presenting multiple options.

Text buttons can be placed on a variety of backgrounds. Until the button is interacted with, its container isnt visible.

202:103.name: Configuration=Elevated, State=pressed, Show Icon=True
202:103.description:
Elevated buttons are are medium-emphasis buttons.
They are essentially filled tonal buttons with a shadow. Only use them when absolutely necessary, such as when the button requires visual separation from a patterned background.

202:87.name: Configuration=Tonal, State=pressed, Show Icon=False
202:87.description:
Tonal buttons are medium-emphasis buttons.
They are an alternative middle ground between filled and outlined buttons. Theyre useful in contexts where a lower-priority button requires slightly more emphasis than an outline would give, such as "Next" in an onboarding flow.

201:30.name: [m3:button] Button
201:30.description: Buttons communicate actions that users can take. They are typically placed throughout your UI, in places like Dialogs, Modal windows, Forms, Cards and Toolbars
